including Waiting for Godot and some

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:45.550
of his other work because
it gave him better control

00:24:45.550 --> 00:24:46.860
and distance from his work.

00:24:46.860 --> 00:24:49.530
What's the reason you have
chosen to write in English?

00:24:49.530 --> 00:24:52.620
&gt;&gt; Edwidge Danticat: Well, I write
in English because I came at 12

00:24:52.620 --> 00:24:56.660
and it's just kind of
flowed into English.

00:24:56.660 --> 00:24:59.520
I think, maybe if I were older

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:02.870
when I got here it would've
been a more difficult choice.

00:25:02.870 --> 00:25:07.700 position:56%
But it's, I always said to people if
I, I think if we're going to a place

00:25:07.700 --> 00:25:09.860
where they speak Spanish,
I'd be writing in Spanish.

00:25:09.860 --> 00:25:11.720
It's just kind of, and, but I,

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:14.660
I did find that when I
started writing initially

00:25:14.660 --> 00:25:18.000
that English was kind of like
a way to, when I would write

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:21.200 position:56%
in my diary I would write in English
so my parents couldn't read it.

00:25:21.200 --> 00:25:26.730
So, it was also, like even
they wouldn't understand also.

00:25:26.730 --> 00:25:31.250
So it was a, it was a layer
removed sort of like my own space.

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:32.870
It was a protective space.

00:25:32.870 --> 00:25:36.070
So it also did serve
that purpose, you know.

00:25:36.070 --> 00:25:37.520
&gt;&gt; Michael Oreskes: Well
similar to Becket in ways.

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:38.950
&gt;&gt; Edwidge Danticat: Exactly yeah.

00:25:38.950 --> 00:25:40.470
&gt;&gt; Michael Oreskes: French
was his third language.

00:25:40.470 --> 00:25:41.770
&gt;&gt; Edwidge Danticat: Yeah.

00:25:41.770 --> 00:25:45.870
And I've been reading, I just
