00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:48.830
who wrote, she wrote
a book in Italian

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:51.080
about her discovery of Italians.

00:25:51.080 --> 00:25:55.550
And, it's really, I think writers
always want to reinvent themselves

00:25:55.550 --> 00:25:58.030
in some way, right, if
you I think for me that's

00:25:58.030 --> 00:26:01.210
where coughing genres come
in like going from the adult

00:26:01.210 --> 00:26:04.500
to picture book, like you feel
like you want to be refreshed.

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:07.520
Right? And, language
is certainly one way.

00:26:07.520 --> 00:26:11.790
And it becomes, I'm a little bit
relieved all the time I see my

00:26:11.790 --> 00:26:14.220
relatives they'll be a year
before like my relatives

00:26:14.220 --> 00:26:15.520
in Haiti will read the book.

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:18.870
So, I always feel like okay
they're like it'll be a year less

00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:21.420
but they'll be mad if I
said something that they.

00:26:21.420 --> 00:26:24.980
So, there's a kind of also
freedom in other languages

00:26:24.980 --> 00:26:27.260
that I think like, especially

00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:30.800
in [inaudible] book she describes
very beautifully about stepping

00:26:30.800 --> 00:26:33.170
over boundaries that you
think you already have

00:26:33.170 --> 00:26:35.150
and whether they're
linguistic boundaries

00:26:35.150 --> 00:26:36.760
or they're genres boundaries,

00:26:36.760 --> 00:26:40.090
but it just offers this
kind of freedom to it.

00:26:40.090 --> 00:26:42.550
&gt;&gt; Michael Oreskes: Do your
relatives get mad very often?

00:26:42.550 --> 00:26:44.350
&gt;&gt; Edwidge Danticat: Not very
